Paragraph: (1) The party was to be our brother and sister, Henry, John—and Miss Smith. (2) My friend Robert could not resist. (3) They called for him in their way; were all extremely amused; and my brother asked him to dine with them the next day—which he did—and in the course of that visit (as I understand) he found an opportunity of speaking to Harriet; and certainly did not speak in vain. (4) She made him, by her acceptance, as happy even as he is deserving. (5) He came down by yesterday’s coach, and was with me this morning immediately after breakfast, to report his proceedings, first on my affairs, and then on his own. (6) This is all that I can relate of the how, where, and when. (7) Your friend Harriet will make a much longer history when you see her. (8) She will give you all the minute particulars, which only woman’s language can make interesting. (9) In our communications we deal only in the great. (10) However, I must say, that Robert Martin’s heart seemed forhim, and tome, very overflowing; and that he did mention, without its being much to the purpose, that on quitting their box at Astley’s, my brother took charge of Mrs. John Knightley and little John, and he followed with Miss Smith and Henry; and that at one time they were in such a crowd, as to make Miss Smith rather uneasy.”



He stopped. (11) Emma dared not attempt any immediate reply. (12) To speak, she was sure would be to betray a most unreasonable degree of happiness. (13) She must wait a moment, or he would think her mad. (14) Her silence disturbed him; and after observing her a little while, he added,



“Emma, my love, you said that this circumstance would not now make you unhappy; but I am afraid it gives you more pain than you expected. (15) His situation is an evil—but you must consider it as what satisfies your friend; and I will answer for your thinking better and better of him as you know him more. (16) His good sense and good principles would delight you. (17) As far as the man is concerned, you could not wish your friend in better hands. (18) His rank in society I would alter if I could, which is saying a great deal I assure you, Emma. (19) You laugh at me about William Larkins; but I could quite as ill spare Robert Martin.”



He wanted her to look up and smile; and having now brought herself not to smile too broadly—she did—cheerfully answering,



“You need not be at any pains to reconcile me to the match. (20) I think Harriet is doing extremely well.Herconnexions may be worse thanhis. (21) In respectability of character, there can be no doubt that they are. (22) I have been silent from surprize merely, excessive surprize. (23) You cannot imagine how suddenly it has come on me! (24) how peculiarly unprepared I was! (25) for I had reason to believe her very lately more determined against him, much more, than she was before.”



“You ought to know your friend best,” replied Mr. Knightley; “but I should say she was a good-tempered, soft-hearted girl, not likely to be very, very determined against any young man who told her he loved her.”



Emma could not help laughing as she answered, “Upon my word, I believe you know her quite as well as I do. (26) But, Mr. Knightley, are you perfectly sure that she has absolutely and downrightacceptedhim. (27) I could suppose she might in time—but can she already? (28) Did not you misunderstand him? (29) You were both talking of other things; of business, shows of cattle, or new drills—and might not you, in the confusion of so many subjects, mistake him? (30) It was not Harriet’s hand that he was certain of—it was the dimensions of some famous ox.”



The contrast between the countenance and air of Mr. Knightley and Robert Martin was, at this moment, so strong to Emma’s feelings, and so strong was the recollection of all that had so recently passed on Harriet’s side, so fresh the sound of those words, spoken with such emphasis, “No, I hope I know better than to think of Robert Martin,” that she was really expecting the intelligence to prove, in some measure, premature. (31) It could not be otherwise. (32) “Do you dare say this?” cried Mr. Knightley. (33) “Do you dare to suppose me so great a blockhead, as not to know what a man is talking of? (34) What do you deserve?”

“Oh! (35) I always deserve the best treatment, because I never put up with any other; and, therefore, you must give me a plain, direct answer. (36) Are you quite sure that you understand the terms on which Mr. Martin and Harriet now are?”



“I am quite sure,” he replied, speaking very distinctly, “that he told me she had accepted him; and that there was no obscurity, nothing doubtful, in the words he used; and I think I can give you a proof that it must be so. (37) He asked my opinion as to what he was now to do. (38) He knew of no one but Mrs. Goddard to whom he could apply for information of her relations or friends. (39) Could I mention any thing more fit to be done, than to go to Mrs. Goddard? (40) I assured him that I could not. (41) Then, he said, he would endeavour to see her in the course of this day.”



“I am perfectly satisfied,” replied Emma, with the brightest smiles, “and most sincerely wish them happy.”



“You are materially changed since we talked on this subject before.”



“I hope so—for at that time I was a fool.”



“And I am changed also; for I am now very willing to grant you all Harriet’s good qualities. (42) I have taken some pains for your sake, and for Robert Martin’s sake, (whom I have always had reason to believe as much in love with her as ever,) to get acquainted with her.



